{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631743"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:33:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:33:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17395"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17395"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.07,0.14,0.73,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10085"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70428"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10085"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17395"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55892"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6689"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23602"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23604"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23635"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70428","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70428"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe coeliac axis is a major branch of the abdominal aorta that supplies blood to several upper abdominal organs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes its major branches?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Splenic, short gastric and left gastroepiploic arteries","Left gastric, right gastric and gastroduodenal arteries","Superior mesenteric, inferior mesenteric and splenic arteries","Left gastric, splenic and common hepatic arteries","Common hepatic, proper hepatic and right gastric arteries"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe coeliac artery divides into three major branches: the \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft gastric artery\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Esplenic artery\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ecommon hepatic artery \u003C/strong\u003E(Image 1, 2). This trifurcation is also known as the coeliac axis or coeliac trunk. This CT angiogram shows the coeliac axis, the superior mesenteric artery and the renal arteries (Image 3).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esplenic, short gastric and left gastroepiploic arteries\u003C/strong\u003E - The short gastric and left gastroepiploic arteries are branches of the splenic artery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft gastric, right gastric and gastroduodenal arteries\u003C/strong\u003E - The right gastric and gastroduodenal arteries are branches of the common hepatic artery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior mesenteric, inferior mesenteric and splenic arteries\u003C/strong\u003E - The superior and inferior mesenteric arteries are separate branches of the abdominal aorta\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecommon hepatic, proper hepatic and right gastric arteries\u003C/strong\u003E - The proper hepatic and right gastric arteries are branches of the common hepatic artery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe coeliac artery arises from the abdominal aorta at the level of thoracic vertebra T12 and supplies blood to the foregut derivatives including the stomach, proximal duodenum, liver, gallbladder, pancreas and spleen.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The coeliac artery supplies the foregut derivatives including the stomach, proximal duodenum, liver, gallbladder, pancreas and spleen.","The coeliac artery branches into three major vessels: left gastric, common hepatic and splenic arteries.","The coeliac artery arises from the abdominal aorta at the level of thoracic vertebra T12."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cCeliac Trunk\u201d by Dennis M DePace, PhD is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons\u00a0Attribution-Share Alike 4.0 Unported\u00a0license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0) \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Celiac_Trunk_and_Branches.jpg\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55892"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17395"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21313"},{"type":"media","id":"21318"},{"type":"media","id":"21319"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21313"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/kpbAvTSTJ7gLUFJIcpooKII1EbsQne.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/kpbAvTSTJ7gLUFJIcpooKII1EbsQne.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":528,"height":405}},{"type":"media","id":"21318","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21318"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/I1XsPMivJyUJjSBvcQDszpVMMKoaPc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/I1XsPMivJyUJjSBvcQDszpVMMKoaPc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":618,"height":480}},{"type":"media","id":"21319","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21319"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cVWjlmH8aL4Z0iReuC8Pp2oPJXOWRw.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c